# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aho-corasick-algorithm
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] In computer science, the **Aho–Corasick algorithm** is a string-searching algorithm invented by Alfred V.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] It is a kind of dictionary-matching algorithm that locates elements of a finite set of strings (the "dictionary") within an input text.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] The complexity of the algorithm is linear in the length of the strings plus the length of the searched text plus the number of output matches.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] Because all matches are found, multiple matches will be returned for one string location if multiple strings from the dictionary match at that location (e.g. dictionary = a, aa, aaa, aaaa and input string is aaaa).
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] Informally, the algorithm creates a trie using the strings in the dictionary and then constructs a finite-state machine from the trie by adding additional links between the nodes.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] This allows the automaton to transition between string matches without the need for backtracking.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] When the string dictionary is known in advance (e.g. a computer virus database), the construction of the automaton can be performed once off-line and the compiled automaton stored for later use.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] In this case, its run time is linear in the length of the input plus the number of matched entries.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] The Aho—Corasick string-matching algorithm formed the basis of the original Unix command fgrep.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] Like many inventions at Bell Labs at the time, the Aho–Corasick algorithm was created serendipitously with a conversation between the two after a seminar by Aho.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] Corasick was an information scientist who got her PhD a year earlier at Lehigh University.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] There, she did her dissertation on securing proprietary data within open systems, through the lens of both the commercial, legal, and government structures and the technical tools that were emerging at the time.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] In a similar realm, at Bell Labs, she was building a tool for researchers to learn about current work being done by government contractors by searching government-provided tapes of publications.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] She had written a primitive keyword-by-keyword search program to find chosen keywords within the tapes, but it scaled poorly with many keywords; One of the bibliographers using her algorithm hit the $600 usage limit on the Bell Labs machines before their search finished.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] She ended up attending a seminar on algorithm design by Aho, and afterwards they got to speaking about her work and this problem.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] Aho suggested improving the efficiency of the program using the approach of the now Aho–Corasick algorithm, and Corasick designed a program based on those insights.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] This lowered the running cost of that bibliographer's search from over $600 to just $25.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] In this example, we will consider a dictionary consisting of the following words: {a, ab, bab, bc, bca, c, caa}.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] The graph below is the Aho–Corasick data structure constructed from the specified dictionary, with each row in the table representing a node in the trie, with the column path indicating the (unique) sequence of characters from the root to the node.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] The data structure has one node for every prefix of every string in the dictionary.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] So if (bca) is in the dictionary, then there will be nodes for (bca), (bc), (b), and ().
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] If a node is in the dictionary then it is a blue node.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] There is a black directed "child" arc from each node to a node whose name is found by appending one character.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] So there is a black arc from (bc) to (bca).
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] There is a blue directed "suffix" arc from each node to the node that is the longest possible strict suffix of it in the graph.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] For example, for node (caa), its strict suffixes are (aa) and (a) and ().
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] The longest of these that exists in the graph is (a).
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] So there is a blue arc from (caa) to (a).
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] The blue arcs can be computed in linear time by performing a breadth-first search [potential suffix node will always be at lower level] starting from the root.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] The target for the blue arc of a visited node can be found by following its parent's blue arc to its longest suffix node and searching for a child of the suffix node whose character matches that of the visited node.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] If the character does not exist as a child, we can find the next longest suffix (following the blue arc again) and then search for the character.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] We can do this until we either find the character (as child of a node) or we reach the root (which will always be a suffix of every string).
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] There is a green "dictionary suffix" arc from each node to the next node in the dictionary that can be reached by following blue arcs.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] For example, there is a green arc from (bca) to (a) because (a) is the first node in the dictionary (i.e. a blue node) that is reached when following the blue arcs to (ca) and then on to (a).
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] The green arcs can be computed in linear time by repeatedly traversing blue arcs until a blue node is found, and memoizing this information.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] At each step, the current node is extended by finding its child, and if that doesn't exist, finding its suffix's child, and if that doesn't work, finding its suffix's suffix's child, and so on, finally ending in the root node if nothing's seen before.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] When the algorithm reaches a node, it outputs all the dictionary entries that end at the current character position in the input text.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] This is done by printing every node reached by following the dictionary suffix links, starting from that node, and continuing until it reaches a node with no dictionary suffix link.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] In addition, the node itself is printed, if it is a dictionary entry.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] The original Aho–Corasick algorithm assumes that the set of search strings is fixed.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] It does not directly apply to applications in which new search strings are added during application of the algorithm.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] An example is an interactive indexing program, in which the user goes through the text and highlights new words or phrases to index as they see them.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/aho-corasick-algorithm] Bertrand Meyer introduced an incremental version of the algorithm in which the search string set can be incrementally extended during the search, retaining the algorithmic complexity of the original.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] In computer science, the **Boyer–Moore string-search algorithm** is an efficient string-searching algorithm that is the standard benchmark for practical string-search literature.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The original paper contained static tables for computing the pattern shifts without an explanation of how to produce them.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The algorithm for producing the tables was published in a follow-on paper; this paper contained errors which were later corrected by Wojciech Rytter in 1980.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The algorithm preprocesses the string being searched for (the pattern), but not the string being searched in (the text).
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] It is thus well-suited for applications in which the pattern is much shorter than the text or where it persists across multiple searches.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The Boyer–Moore algorithm uses information gathered during the preprocess step to skip sections of the text, resulting in a lower constant factor than many other string search algorithms.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] In general, the algorithm runs faster as the pattern length increases.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The key features of the algorithm are to match on the tail of the pattern rather than the head, and to skip along the text in jumps of multiple characters rather than searching every single character in the text.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The Boyer–Moore algorithm searches for occurrences of P in T by performing explicit character comparisons at different alignments.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Instead of a brute-force search of all alignments (of which there are ⁠ $n-m+1$ ⁠), Boyer–Moore uses information gained by preprocessing P to skip as many alignments as possible.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Previous to the introduction of this algorithm, the usual way to search within text was to examine each character of the text for the first character of the pattern.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Once that was found the subsequent characters of the text would be compared to the characters of the pattern.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] If no match occurred then the text would again be checked character by character in an effort to find a match.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Thus almost every character in the text needs to be examined.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The key insight in this algorithm is that if the end of the pattern is compared to the text, then jumps along the text can be made rather than checking every character of the text.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The reason that this works is that in lining up the pattern against the text, the last character of the pattern is compared to the character in the text.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] If the characters do not match, there is no need to continue searching backwards along the text.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] If the character in the text does not match any of the characters in the pattern, then the next character in the text to check is located m characters farther along the text, where m is the length of the pattern.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] If the character in the text *is* in the pattern, then a partial shift of the pattern along the text is done to line up along the matching character and the process is repeated.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Jumping along the text to make comparisons rather than checking every character in the text decreases the number of comparisons that have to be made, which is the key to the efficiency of the algorithm.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] More formally, the algorithm begins at alignment ⁠ $k=m$ ⁠, so the start of P is aligned with the start of T.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Characters in P and T are then compared starting at index m in P and k in T, moving backward.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The strings are matched from the end of P to the start of P.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The comparisons continue until either the beginning of P is reached (which means there is a match) or a mismatch occurs upon which the alignment is shifted forward (to the right) according to the maximum value permitted by a number of rules.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The comparisons are performed again at the new alignment, and the process repeats until the alignment is shifted past the end of T, which means no further matches will be found.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The shift rules are implemented as constant-time table lookups, using tables generated during the preprocessing of P.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] A shift is calculated by applying two rules: the bad-character rule and the good-suffix rule.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The actual shifting offset is the maximum of the shifts calculated by these rules.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The bad-character rule considers the character in T at which the comparison process failed (assuming such a failure occurred).
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The next occurrence of that character to the left in P is found, and a shift which brings that occurrence in line with the mismatched occurrence in T is proposed.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] If the mismatched character does not occur to the left in P, a shift is proposed that moves the entirety of P past the point of mismatch.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Methods vary on the exact form the table for the bad-character rule should take, but a simple constant-time lookup solution is as follows: create a 2D table which is indexed first by the index of the character c in the alphabet and second by the index i in the pattern.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] This lookup will return the occurrence of c in P with the next-highest index ⁠ $j<i$ ⁠ or -1 if there is no such occurrence.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The proposed shift will then be ⁠ $i-j$ ⁠, with ⁠ $O(1)$ ⁠ lookup time and ⁠ $O(km)$ ⁠ space, assuming a finite alphabet of length k.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The C and Java implementations below have a ⁠ $O(k)$ ⁠ space complexity (make_delta1, makeCharTable).
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] This is the same as the original delta1 and the BMH bad-character table.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] This table maps a character at position ⁠ i ⁠ to shift by ⁠ $\operatorname {len} (p)-1-i$ ⁠, with the last instance—the least shift amount—taking precedence.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] All unused characters are set as ⁠ $\operatorname {len} (p)$ ⁠ as a sentinel value.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The good-suffix rule is markedly more complex in both concept and implementation than the bad-character rule.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Like the bad-character rule, it also exploits the algorithm's feature of comparisons beginning at the end of the pattern and proceeding towards the pattern's start.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The good-suffix rule requires two tables: one for use in the general case (where a copy ***t′*** is found), and another for use when the general case returns no meaningful result.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] These tables will be designated L and H respectively.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Both of these tables are constructible in ⁠ $O(m)$ ⁠ time and use ⁠ $O(m)$ ⁠ space.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The alignment shift for index i in P is given by ⁠ $m-L[i]$ ⁠ or ⁠ $m-H[i]$ ⁠.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] H should only be used if ⁠ $L[i]$ ⁠ is zero or a match has been found.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Index 0, no characters matched, the character read was not an N.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Since there are plenty of letters in the pattern that are also not N, we have minimal information here - shifting by 1 is the least interesting result.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Index 1, we matched the N, and it was preceded by something other than A.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Now look at the pattern starting from the end, where do we have N preceded by something other than A?
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] There are two other N's, but both are preceded by A.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] That means no part of the good suffix can be useful to us—shift by the full pattern length 8.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Index 2: We matched the AN, and it was preceded by not M.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] In the middle of the pattern there is a AN preceded by P, so it becomes the shift candidate.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Shifting that AN to the right to line up with our match is a shift of 3.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Index 3 & up: the matched suffixes do not match anything else in the pattern, but the trailing suffix AN matches the start of the pattern, so the shifts here are all 6.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] A simple but important optimization of Boyer–Moore was put forth by Zvi Galil in 1979.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] As opposed to shifting, the Galil rule deals with speeding up the actual comparisons done at each alignment by skipping sections that are known to match.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Suppose that at an alignment *k*1, ***P*** is compared with ***T*** down to character ***c*** of ***T***.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Then if ***P*** is shifted to *k*2 such that its left end is between ***c*** and *k*1, in the next comparison phase a prefix of ***P*** must match the substring ***T***[(*k*2 - *n*)..*k*1].
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Thus if the comparisons get down to position *k*1 of ***T***, an occurrence of ***P*** can be recorded without explicitly comparing past *k*1.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] In addition to increasing the efficiency of Boyer–Moore, the Galil rule is required for proving linear-time execution in the worst case.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The Galil rule, in its original version, is only effective for versions that output multiple matches.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] It updates the substring range only on ***c*** = 0, i.e. a full match.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] A generalized version for dealing with submatches was reported in 1985 as the Apostolico–Giancarlo algorithm.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The Boyer–Moore algorithm as presented in the original paper has worst-case running time of ⁠ $O(n+m)$ ⁠ only if the pattern does *not* appear in the text.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] This was first proved by Knuth, Morris, and Pratt in 1977, followed by Guibas and Odlyzko in 1980 with an upper bound of 5*n* comparisons in the worst case.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Richard Cole gave a proof with an upper bound of 3*n* comparisons in the worst case in 1991.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] There is a simple modification of the BM algorithm which improves the bound to 2*n*.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] When the pattern *does* occur in the text, running time of the original algorithm is ⁠ $O(nm)$ ⁠ in the worst case.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] This is easy to see when both pattern and text consist solely of the same repeated character.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] However, inclusion of the Galil rule results in linear runtime across all cases.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Knuth, Morris and Pratt also showed that for a *random* text, the average number of character comparisons is bounded by $O\left({\frac {n\log _{k}m}{m}}\right)$ , where k is the alphabet size.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Various implementations exist in different programming languages.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] In C++ it is part of the Standard Library since C++17 and Boost provides the generic Boyer–Moore search implementation under the *Algorithm* library.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] In Go (programming language) there is an implementation in search.go.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] D (programming language) uses a BoyerMooreFinder for predicate based matching within ranges as a part of the Phobos Runtime Library.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The Boyer–Moore algorithm is also used in GNU's grep.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The Boyer–Moore–Horspool algorithm is a simplification of the Boyer–Moore algorithm using only the bad-character rule.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The Apostolico–Giancarlo algorithm speeds up the process of checking whether a match has occurred at the given alignment by skipping explicit character comparisons.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] This uses information gleaned during the pre-processing of the pattern in conjunction with suffix match lengths recorded at each match attempt.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Storing suffix match lengths requires an additional table equal in size to the text being searched.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The Raita algorithm improves the performance of Boyer–Moore–Horspool algorithm.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The searching pattern of particular sub-string in a given string is different from Boyer–Moore–Horspool algorithm.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] *Deterministic* refers to the uniqueness of the computation run.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] In search of the simplest models to capture finite-state machines, Warren McCulloch and Walter Pitts were among the first researchers to introduce a concept similar to finite automata in 1943.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] The figure illustrates a deterministic finite automaton using a state diagram.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] In this example automaton, there are three states: S0, S1, and S2 (denoted graphically by circles).
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] The automaton takes a finite sequence of 0s and 1s as input.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] For each state, there is a transition arrow leading out to a next state for both 0 and 1.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] Upon reading a symbol, a DFA jumps *deterministically* from one state to another by following the transition arrow.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] For example, if the automaton is currently in state S0 and the current input symbol is 1, then it deterministically jumps to state S1.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] A DFA has a *start state* (denoted graphically by an arrow coming in from nowhere) where computations begin, and a set of *accept states* (denoted graphically by a double circle) which help define when a computation is successful.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] A DFA is defined as an abstract mathematical concept, but is often implemented in hardware and software for solving various specific problems such as lexical analysis and pattern matching.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] For example, a DFA can model software that decides whether or not online user input such as email addresses are syntactically valid.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] DFAs have been generalized to *nondeterministic finite automata (NFA)* which may have several arrows of the same label starting from a state.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] Using the powerset construction method, every NFA can be translated to a DFA that recognizes the same language.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] DFAs, and NFAs as well, recognize exactly the set of regular languages.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] Let *w* = *a*1*a*2...*an* be a string over the alphabet Σ.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] In words, the first condition says that the machine starts in the start state *q*0.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] The second condition says that given each character of string w, the machine will transition from state to state according to the transition function δ.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] The last condition says that the machine accepts w if the last input of w causes the machine to halt in one of the accepting states.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] Otherwise, it is said that the automaton *rejects* the string.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] The set of strings that M accepts is the language *recognized* by M and this language is denoted by *L*(*M*).
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] A deterministic finite automaton without accept states and without a starting state is known as a transition system or semiautomaton.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] For more comprehensive introduction of the formal definition see automata theory.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] The following example is of a DFA M, with a binary alphabet, which requires that the input contains an even number of 0s.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] The state *S*1 represents that there has been an even number of 0s in the input so far, while *S*2 signifies an odd number.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] A 1 in the input does not change the state of the automaton.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] When the input ends, the state will show whether the input contained an even number of 0s or not.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] If the input did contain an even number of 0s, M will finish in state *S*1, an accepting state, so the input string will be accepted.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] The language recognized by M is the regular language given by the regular expression `(1*) (0 (1*) 0 (1*))*`, where `*` is the Kleene star, e.g., `1*` denotes any number (possibly zero) of consecutive ones.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] According to the above definition, deterministic finite automata are always *complete*: they define from each state a transition for each input symbol.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] While this is the most common definition, some authors use the term deterministic finite automaton for a slightly different notion: an automaton that defines *at most* one transition for each state and each input symbol; the transition function is allowed to be partial.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] When no transition is defined, such an automaton halts.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] A **local automaton** is a DFA, not necessarily complete, for which all edges with the same label lead to a single vertex.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] Local automata accept the class of local languages, those for which membership of a word in the language is determined by a "sliding window" of length two on the word.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] A **Myhill graph** over an alphabet *A* is a directed graph with vertex set *A* and subsets of vertices labelled "start" and "finish".
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] The language accepted by a Myhill graph is the set of directed paths from a start vertex to a finish vertex: the graph thus acts as an automaton.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] The class of languages accepted by Myhill graphs is the class of local languages.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] When the start state and accept states are ignored, a DFA of n states and an alphabet of size k can be seen as a digraph of n vertices in which all vertices have k out-arcs labeled 1, ..., *k* (a k-out digraph).
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] It is known that when *k* ≥ 2 is a fixed integer, with high probability, the largest strongly connected component (SCC) in such a k-out digraph chosen uniformly at random is of linear size and it can be reached by all vertices.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] It has also been proven that if k is allowed to increase as n increases, then the whole digraph has a phase transition for strong connectivity similar to Erdős–Rényi model for connectivity.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] In a random DFA, the maximum number of vertices reachable from one vertex is very close to the number of vertices in the largest SCC with high probability.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] This is also true for the largest induced sub-digraph of minimum in-degree one, which can be seen as a directed version of 1-core.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] If DFAs recognize the languages that are obtained by applying an operation on the DFA recognizable languages then DFAs are said to be closed under the operation.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] The DFAs are closed under the following operations.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] For each operation, an optimal construction with respect to the number of states has been determined in state complexity research.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] Since DFAs are equivalent to nondeterministic finite automata (NFA), these closures may also be proved using closure properties of NFA.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] A run of a given DFA can be seen as a sequence of compositions of a very general formulation of the transition function with itself.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] For a given input symbol $a\in \Sigma$ , one may construct a transition function $\delta _{a}:Q\rightarrow Q$ by defining $\delta _{a}(q)=\delta (q,a)$ for all $q\in Q$ .
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] (This trick is called currying.) From this perspective, $\delta _{a}$ "acts" on a state in Q to yield another state.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] One may then consider the result of function composition repeatedly applied to the various functions $\delta _{a}$ , $\delta _{b}$ , and so on.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] Given a pair of letters $a,b\in \Sigma$ , one may define a new function ${\widehat {\delta }}_{ab}=\delta _{a}\circ \delta _{b}$ , where $\circ$ denotes function composition.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] ${\widehat {\delta }}$ is defined for all words $w\in \Sigma ^{*}$ .
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] A run of the DFA is a sequence of compositions of ${\widehat {\delta }}$ with itself.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] Repeated function composition forms a monoid.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] For the transition functions, this monoid is known as the transition monoid, or sometimes the *transformation semigroup*.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] The construction can also be reversed: given a ${\widehat {\delta }}$ , one can reconstruct a $\delta$ , and so the two descriptions are equivalent.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] DFAs are one of the most practical models of computation, since there is a trivial linear time, constant-space, online algorithm to simulate a DFA on a stream of input.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] DFAs are equivalent in computing power to nondeterministic finite automata (NFAs).
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] This is because, firstly any DFA is also an NFA, so an NFA can do what a DFA can do.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] Also, given an NFA, using the powerset construction one can build a DFA that recognizes the same language as the NFA, although the DFA could have exponentially larger number of states than the NFA.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] However, even though NFAs are computationally equivalent to DFAs, the above-mentioned problems are not necessarily solved efficiently also for NFAs.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] The non-universality problem for NFAs is PSPACE complete since there are small NFAs with shortest rejecting word in exponential size.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] A DFA is universal if and only if all states are final states, but this does not hold for NFAs.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] The Equality, Inclusion and Minimization Problems are also PSPACE complete since they require forming the complement of an NFA which results in an exponential blow up of size.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] On the other hand, finite-state automata are of strictly limited power in the languages they can recognize; many simple languages, including any problem that requires more than constant space to solve, cannot be recognized by a DFA.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] The classic example of a simply described language that no DFA can recognize is bracket or Dyck language, i.e., the language that consists of properly paired brackets such as word "(()())".
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] Intuitively, no DFA can recognize the Dyck language because DFAs are not capable of counting: a DFA-like automaton needs to have a state to represent any possible number of "currently open" parentheses, meaning it would need an unbounded number of states.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] Another simpler example is the language consisting of strings of the form *anbn* for some finite but arbitrary number of *a*'s, followed by an equal number of *b*'s.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] Given a set of *positive* words $S^{+}\subset \Sigma ^{*}$ and a set of *negative* words $S^{-}\subset \Sigma ^{*}$ one can construct a DFA that accepts all words from $S^{+}$ and rejects all words from $S^{-}$ : this problem is called *DFA identification* (synthesis, learning).
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] While *some* DFA can be constructed in linear time, the problem of identifying a DFA with the minimal number of states is NP-complete.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] The first algorithm for minimal DFA identification has been proposed by Trakhtenbrot and Barzdin and is called the *TB-algorithm*.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] However, the TB-algorithm assumes that all words from $\Sigma$ up to a given length are contained in either $S^{+}\cup S^{-}$ .
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] Lang proposed an extension of the TB-algorithm that does not use any assumptions about $S^{+}$ and $S^{-}$ , the *Traxbar* algorithm.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] However, Traxbar does not guarantee the minimality of the constructed DFA.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] Gold also proposed a heuristic algorithm for minimal DFA identification.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] Gold's algorithm assumes that $S^{+}$ and $S^{-}$ contain a *characteristic set* of the regular language; otherwise, the constructed DFA will be inconsistent either with $S^{+}$ or $S^{-}$ .
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] Other notable DFA identification algorithms include the RPNI algorithm, the Blue-Fringe evidence-driven state-merging algorithm, and Windowed-EDSM.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] Yet another step forward is due to application of SAT solvers by Marjin J.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] Verwer: the minimal DFA identification problem is reduced to deciding the satisfiability of a Boolean formula.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] Though this approach allows finding the minimal DFA, it suffers from exponential blow-up of execution time when the size of input data increases.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] Therefore, Heule and Verwer's initial algorithm has later been augmented with making several steps of the EDSM algorithm prior to SAT solver execution: the DFASAT algorithm.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] This allows reducing the search space of the problem, but leads to loss of the minimality guarantee.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] Another way of reducing the search space has been proposed by Ulyantsev et al. by means of new symmetry breaking predicates based on the breadth-first search algorithm: the sought DFA's states are constrained to be numbered according to the BFS algorithm launched from the initial state.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] This approach reduces the search space by $C!$ by eliminating isomorphic automata.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] The machine always accepts a regular language.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/deterministic-finite-automaton] There must exist at least one element of the set F (a **HALT** state) for the language to be nonempty.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] In theoretical computer science, a **finite-state machine** (**FSM**) or **finite-state automaton** (**FSA**, plural: *automata*), **finite automaton**, or simply a **state machine**, is a mathematical model of computation.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] It is an abstract machine that can be in exactly one of a finite number of *states* at any given time.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] The FSM can change from one state to another in response to some inputs; the change from one state to another is called a *transition*.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] An FSM is defined by a list of its states, its initial state, and the inputs that trigger each transition.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] Finite-state machines are of two types—deterministic finite-state machines and non-deterministic finite-state machines.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] For any non-deterministic finite-state machine, an equivalent deterministic one can be constructed.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] The behavior of state machines can be observed in many devices in modern society that perform a predetermined sequence of actions depending on a sequence of events with which they are presented.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] The finite-state machine has less computational power than some other models of computation such as the Turing machine.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] The computational power distinction means there are computational tasks that a Turing machine can do but an FSM cannot.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] This is because an FSM's memory is limited by the number of states it has.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] A finite-state machine has the same computational power as a Turing machine that is restricted such that its head may only perform "read" operations, and always has to move from left to right.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] FSMs are studied in the more general field of automata theory.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] An example of a simple mechanism that can be modeled by a state machine is a turnstile.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] A turnstile, used to control access to subways and amusement park rides, is a gate with three rotating arms at waist height, one across the entryway.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] Initially the arms are locked, blocking the entry, preventing patrons from passing through.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] Depositing a coin or token in a slot on the turnstile unlocks the arms, allowing a single customer to push through.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] After the customer passes through, the arms are locked again until another coin is inserted.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] Considered as a state machine, the turnstile has two possible states: *Locked* and *Unlocked*.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] There are two possible inputs that affect its state: putting a coin in the slot (*coin*) and pushing the arm (*push*).
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] In the locked state, pushing on the arm has no effect; no matter how many times the input *push* is given, it stays in the locked state.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] Putting a coin in – that is, giving the machine a *coin* input – shifts the state from *Locked* to *Unlocked*.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] In the unlocked state, putting additional coins in has no effect; that is, giving additional *coin* inputs does not change the state.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] A customer pushing through the arms gives a *push* input and resets the state to *Locked*.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] The turnstile state machine can also be represented by a directed graph called a state diagram *(above)*.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] Each state is represented by a node (*circle*).
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] Edges (*arrows*) show the transitions from one state to another.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] Each arrow is labeled with the input that triggers that transition.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] An input that doesn't cause a change of state (such as a *coin* input in the *Unlocked* state) is represented by a circular arrow returning to the original state.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] The arrow into the *Locked* node from the black dot indicates it is the initial state.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] A *state* is a description of the status of a system that is waiting to execute a *transition*.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] A transition is a set of actions to be executed when a condition is fulfilled or when an event is received.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] For example, when using an audio system to listen to the radio (the system is in the "radio" state), receiving a "next" stimulus results in moving to the next station.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] When the system is in the "CD" state, the "next" stimulus results in moving to the next track.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] Identical stimuli trigger different actions depending on the current state.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] Several state-transition table types are used.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] The most common representation is shown below: the combination of current state (e.g.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] By itself, the table cannot completely describe the action, so it is common to use footnotes.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] Other related representations may not have this limitation.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] For example, an FSM definition including the full action's information is possible using state tables (see also virtual finite-state machine).
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] The Unified Modeling Language has a notation for describing state machines.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] UML state machines overcome the limitations of traditional finite-state machines while retaining their main benefits.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] UML state machines introduce the new concepts of hierarchically nested states and orthogonal regions, while extending the notion of actions.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] UML state machines have the characteristics of both Mealy machines and Moore machines.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] They support actions that depend on both the state of the system and the triggering event, as in Mealy machines, as well as entry and exit actions, which are associated with states rather than transitions, as in Moore machines.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] SDL embeds basic data types called "Abstract Data Types", an action language, and an execution semantic in order to make the finite-state machine executable.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] There are a large number of variants to represent an FSM such as the one in figure 3.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] In addition to their use in modeling reactive systems presented here, finite-state machines are significant in many different areas, including electrical engineering, linguistics, computer science, philosophy, biology, mathematics, video game programming, and logic.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] Finite-state machines are a class of automata studied in automata theory and the theory of computation.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] In computer science, finite-state machines are widely used in modeling of application behavior (control theory), design of hardware digital systems, software engineering, compilers, network protocols, and computational linguistics.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] Finite-state machines can be subdivided into acceptors, classifiers, transducers and sequencers.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] A (possibly infinite) set of symbol sequences, called a formal language, is a regular language if there is some acceptor that accepts *exactly* that set.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] For example, the set of binary strings with an even number of zeroes is a regular language (cf.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] 5), while the set of all strings whose length is a prime number is not.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] An acceptor could also be described as defining a language that would contain every string accepted by the acceptor but none of the rejected ones; that language is *accepted* by the acceptor.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] By definition, the languages accepted by acceptors are the regular languages.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] The problem of determining the language accepted by a given acceptor is an instance of the algebraic path problem—itself a generalization of the shortest path problem to graphs with edges weighted by the elements of an (arbitrary) semiring.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] An example of an accepting state appears in Fig.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] 5: a deterministic finite automaton (DFA) that detects whether the binary input string contains an even number of 0s.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] The FSM uses only entry actions, i.e., output depends only on state.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] The advantage of the Moore model is a simplification of the behaviour.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] The state machine recognizes two commands: "command_open" and "command_close", which trigger state changes.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] The entry action (E:) in state "Opening" starts a motor opening the door, the entry action in state "Closing" starts a motor in the other direction closing the door.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] States "Opened" and "Closed" stop the motor when fully opened or closed.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] They signal to the outside world (e.g., to other state machines) the situation: "door is open" or "door is closed".
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] The FSM also uses input actions, i.e., output depends on input and state.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] The use of a Mealy FSM leads often to a reduction of the number of states.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] There are two input actions (I:): "start motor to close the door if command_close arrives" and "start motor in the other direction to open the door if command_open arrives".
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] The "opening" and "closing" intermediate states are not shown.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] A further distinction is between *deterministic* (DFA) and *non-deterministic* (NFA, GNFA) automata.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] In a deterministic automaton, every state has exactly one transition for each possible input.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] In a non-deterministic automaton, an input can lead to one, more than one, or no transition for a given state.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] The powerset construction algorithm can transform any nondeterministic automaton into a (usually more complex) deterministic automaton with identical functionality.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] A finite-state machine with only one state is called a "combinatorial FSM".
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] It only allows actions upon transition *into* a state.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] This concept is useful in cases where a number of finite-state machines are required to work together, and when it is convenient to consider a purely combinatorial part as a form of FSM to suit the design tools.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] There are other sets of semantics available to represent state machines.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] For example, there are tools for modeling and designing logic for embedded controllers.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] They combine hierarchical state machines (which usually have more than one current state), flow graphs, and truth tables into one language, resulting in a different formalism and set of semantics.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] These charts, like Harel's original state machines, support hierarchically nested states, orthogonal regions, state actions, and transition actions.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] In accordance with the general classification, the following formal definitions are found.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] For both deterministic and non-deterministic FSMs, it is conventional to allow $\delta$ to be a partial function, i.e. $\delta (s,x)$ does not have to be defined for every combination of $s\in S$ and $x\in \Sigma$ .
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] If an FSM M is in a state s , the next symbol is x and $\delta (s,x)$ is not defined, then M can announce an error (i.e. reject the input).
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] This is useful in definitions of general state machines, but less useful when transforming the machine.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] Some algorithms in their default form may require total functions.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] That is, each formal language accepted by a finite-state machine is accepted by such a kind of restricted Turing machine, and vice versa.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] If the output function depends on the state and input symbol ( $\omega :S\times \Sigma \rightarrow \Gamma$ ) that definition corresponds to the *Mealy model*, and can be modelled as a Mealy machine.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] If the output function depends only on the state ( $\omega :S\rightarrow \Gamma$ ) that definition corresponds to the *Moore model*, and can be modelled as a Moore machine.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] A finite-state machine with no output function at all is known as a semiautomaton or transition system.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] If we disregard the first output symbol of a Moore machine, $\omega (s_{0})$ , then it can be readily converted to an output-equivalent Mealy machine by setting the output function of every Mealy transition (i.e. labeling every edge) with the output symbol given of the destination Moore state.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] The converse transformation is less straightforward because a Mealy machine state may have different output labels on its incoming transitions (edges).
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] Every such state needs to be split in multiple Moore machine states, one for every incident output symbol.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] Optimizing an FSM means finding a machine with the minimum number of states that performs the same function.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] The fastest known algorithm doing this is the Hopcroft minimization algorithm.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] Other techniques include using an implication table, or the Moore reduction procedure.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] Additionally, acyclic FSAs can be minimized in linear time.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] In a digital circuit, an FSM may be built using a programmable logic device, a programmable logic controller, logic gates and flip flops or relays.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] More specifically, a hardware implementation requires a register to store state variables, a block of combinational logic that determines the state transition, and a second block of combinational logic that determines the output of an FSM.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] In a *Medvedev machine*, the output is directly connected to the state flip-flops minimizing the time delay between flip-flops and output.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] Through state encoding for low power state machines may be optimized to minimize power consumption.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] Finite automata are often used in the frontend of programming language compilers.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] Such a frontend may comprise several finite-state machines that implement a lexical analyzer and a parser.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] Starting from a sequence of characters, the lexical analyzer builds a sequence of language tokens (such as reserved words, literals, and identifiers) from which the parser builds a syntax tree.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/finite-state-machine] The lexical analyzer and the parser handle the regular and context-free parts of the programming language's grammar.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] A **string-searching algorithm**, sometimes called **string-matching algorithm**, is an algorithm that searches a body of text for portions that match by pattern.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] In practice, the method of feasible string-search algorithm may be affected by the string encoding.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] In particular, if a variable-width encoding is in use, then it may be slower to find the *N*th character, perhaps requiring time proportional to *N*.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] This may significantly slow some search algorithms.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] One of many possible solutions is to search for the sequence of code units instead, but doing so may produce false matches unless the encoding is specifically designed to avoid it.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] The most basic case of string searching involves one (often very long) string, sometimes called the *haystack*, and one (often very short) string, sometimes called the *needle*.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] The goal is to find one or more occurrences of the needle within the haystack.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] One might request the first occurrence of "to", which is the fourth word; or all occurrences, of which there are 3; or the last, which is the fifth word from the end.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] Very commonly, however, various constraints are added.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] For example, one might want to match the "needle" only where it consists of one (or more) complete words—perhaps defined as *not* having other letters immediately adjacent on either side.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] In that case a search for "hew" or "low" should fail for the example sentence above, even though those literal strings do occur.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] Another common example involves "normalization".
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] Finally, for strings that represent natural language, aspects of the language itself become involved.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] For example, one might wish to find all occurrences of a "word" despite it having alternate spellings, prefixes or suffixes, etc.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] Another more complex type of search is regular expression searching, where the user constructs a pattern of characters or other symbols, and any match to the pattern should fulfill the search.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] where the "?" conventionally makes the preceding character ("u") optional.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] This article mainly discusses algorithms for the simpler kinds of string searching.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] A similar problem introduced in the field of bioinformatics and genomics is the maximal exact matching (MEM).
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] Given two strings, MEMs are common substrings that cannot be extended left or right without causing a mismatch.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] A simple and inefficient way to see where one string occurs inside another is to check at each index, one by one.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] First, we see if there is a copy of the needle starting at the first character of the haystack; if not, we look to see if there's a copy of the needle starting at the second character of the haystack, and so forth.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] In this approach, backtracking is avoided by constructing a deterministic finite automaton (DFA) that recognizes a stored search string.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] These are expensive to construct—they are usually created using the powerset construction—but are very quick to use.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] For example, the DFA shown to the right recognizes the word "MOMMY".
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] This approach is frequently generalized in practice to search for arbitrary regular expressions.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] Knuth–Morris–Pratt computes a DFA that recognizes inputs with the string to search for as a suffix, Boyer–Moore starts searching from the end of the needle, so it can usually jump ahead a whole needle-length at each step.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] Baeza–Yates keeps track of whether the previous *j* characters were a prefix of the search string, and is therefore adaptable to fuzzy string searching.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] The bitap algorithm is an application of Baeza–Yates' approach.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] Faster search algorithms preprocess the text.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] After building a substring index, for example a suffix tree or suffix array, the occurrences of a pattern can be found quickly.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] As an example, a suffix tree can be built in $\Theta (n)$ time, and all z occurrences of a pattern can be found in $O(m)$ time under the assumption that the alphabet has a constant size and all inner nodes in the suffix tree know what leaves are underneath them.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] The latter can be accomplished by running a DFS algorithm from the root of the suffix tree.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] Some search methods, for instance trigram search, are intended to find a "closeness" score between the search string and the text rather than a "match/non-match".
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] These are sometimes called "fuzzy" searches.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] The various algorithms can be classified by the number of patterns each uses.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] In the following compilation, *m* is the length of the pattern, *n* the length of the searchable text, and *k* = |Σ| is the size of the alphabet.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] The **Boyer–Moore string-search algorithm** has been the standard benchmark for the practical string-search literature.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] In the following compilation, *M* is the length of the longest pattern, *m* their total length, *n* the length of the searchable text, *o* the number of occurrences.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] Naturally, the patterns can not be enumerated finitely in this case.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] They are represented usually by a regular grammar or regular expression.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] Other classification approaches are possible.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] One of the most common uses preprocessing as main criteria.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] In real-time string matching, one requires the matcher to output a response after reading each character of the text, that indicates whether this is the last character of a match.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] The response has to be given within constant time.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] For the more lenient version, if one does not mind that the preprocessing time and memory requirement dependend on the size of the alphabet, a real-time solution is provided by automaton matching.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] Zvi Galil developed a method to turn certain algorithms into real-time algorithms, and applied it to produce a variant of the KMP matcher that runs in real time under the strict requirement.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] In this version of the string searching problem, there is a special symbol, ø (read: don't care), which can match any other symbol (including another ø).
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] Don't care symbols can appear either in the pattern or in the text.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] In 2002, an algorithm for this problem that runs in $O(n\log m)$ time has been given by Richard Cole and Ramesh Hariharan, improving on a solution from 1973 by Fischer and Paterson that has complexity $O(n\log m\log k)$ , where *k* is the size of the alphabet.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] Another algorithm, claimed simpler, has been proposed by Clifford and Clifford.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] In computer science, a **trie** (/ˈtraɪ/, /ˈtriː/ ⓘ), also known as a **digital tree** or **prefix tree**, is a specialized search tree data structure used to store and retrieve strings from a dictionary or set.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Unlike a binary search tree, nodes in a trie do not store their associated key.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Instead, each node's *position* within the trie determines its associated key, with the connections between nodes defined by individual characters rather than the entire key.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Tries are particularly effective for tasks such as autocomplete, spell checking, and IP routing, offering advantages over hash tables due to their prefix-based organization and lack of hash collisions.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Every child node shares a common prefix with its parent node, and the root node represents the empty string.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] While basic trie implementations can be memory-intensive, various optimization techniques such as compression and bitwise representations have been developed to improve their efficiency.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] A notable optimization is the radix tree, which provides more efficient prefix-based storage.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] While tries store character strings, they can be adapted to work with any ordered sequence of elements, such as permutations of digits or shapes.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] A notable variant is the **bitwise trie**, which uses individual bits from fixed-length binary data (such as integers or memory addresses) as keys.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] The idea of a trie for representing a set of strings was first abstractly described by Axel Thue in 1912.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Tries were first described in a computer context by René de la Briandais in 1959.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] The idea was independently described in 1960 by Edward Fredkin, who coined the term *trie*, pronouncing it /ˈtriː/ (as "tree"), after the middle syllable of *retrieval*.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] However, other authors pronounce it /ˈtraɪ/ (as "try"), in an attempt to distinguish it verbally from "tree".
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Tries are a form of string-indexed look-up data structure, which is used to store a dictionary list of words that can be searched on in a manner that allows for efficient generation of completion lists.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] A prefix trie is an ordered tree data structure used in the representation of a set of strings over a finite alphabet set, which allows efficient storage of words with common prefixes.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Tries can be efficacious on string-searching algorithms such as predictive text, approximate string matching, and spell checking in comparison to binary search trees.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] A trie can be seen as a tree-shaped deterministic finite automaton.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Tries support various operations: insertion, deletion, and lookup of a string key.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Tries are composed of nodes that contain links, which either point to other suffix child nodes or *null*.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] As for every tree, each node except the root is pointed to by only one other node, called its *parent*.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Each node contains as many links as the number of characters in the applicable alphabet (although tries tend to have a substantial number of null links).
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] In some cases, the alphabet used is simply that of the character encoding—resulting in, for example, a size of 128 in the case of ASCII.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Each node contains one possible link to a prefix of strong keys of the set.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] A basic structure type of nodes in the trie is as follows: ${\text{Node}}$ may contain an optional ${\text{Value}}$ , which is associated with the key that corresponds to the node.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Searching for a value in a trie is guided by the characters in the search string key, as each node in the trie contains a corresponding link to each possible character in the given string.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Thus, following the string within the trie yields the associated value for the given string key.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] A null link during the search indicates the inexistence of the key.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] The following pseudocode implements the search procedure for a given string key in a rooted trie x.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] In the above pseudocode, x and key correspond to the pointer of the trie's root node and the string key, respectively.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] The search operation takes $O(m)$ time, where m is the size of the string parameter key.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] In a balanced binary search tree, on the other hand, it takes $O(m\log n)$ time, in the worst case, since key needs to be compared with $O(\log n)$ other keys and each comparison takes $O(m)$ time, in the worst case.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] The trie occupies less space, in comparison with a binary search tree, in the case of a large number of short strings, since nodes share common initial string subsequences and store the keys implicitly.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Insertion into a trie is guided by using the character sets as indexes to the children array until the last character of the string key is reached.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Each node in the trie corresponds to one call of the radix sorting routine, as the trie structure reflects the execution pattern of the top-down radix sort.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] If null links are encountered before reaching the last character of the string key, new nodes are created.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] The input value is assigned to the value of the last node traversed, which is the node that corresponds to the key.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Deletion of a key–value pair from a trie involves finding the node corresponding to the key, setting its value to null, and recursively removing nodes that have no children.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] The procedure begins by examining key; an empty string indicates arrival at the node corresponding to the (original) key, in which case its value is set to null.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] If the node, then, has null value and no children, it is removed from the trie by returning null; otherwise, the node is kept by returning the node itself.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] However, tries are less efficient than a hash table when the data is directly accessed on a secondary storage device such as a hard disk drive that has higher random access time than the main memory.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Tries can be represented in several ways, corresponding to different trade-offs between memory use and speed of the operations.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Using a vector of pointers for representing a trie consumes enormous space; however, memory space can be reduced at the expense of running time if a singly linked list is used for each node vector, as most entries of the vector contains ${\text{nil}}$ .
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Techniques such as *alphabet reduction* may reduce the large space requirements by reinterpreting the original string as a longer string over a smaller alphabet.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] For example, a string of n bytes can alternatively be regarded as a string of 2*n* four-bit units.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] This can reduce memory usage by a factor of eight; but lookups need to visit twice as many nodes in the worst case.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Another technique includes storing a vector of 256 ASCII pointers as a bitmap of 256 bits representing ASCII alphabet, which reduces the size of individual nodes dramatically.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Bitwise tries are used to address the enormous space requirement for the trie nodes in a naive simple pointer vector implementations.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Each character in the string key set is represented via individual bits, which are used to traverse the trie over a string key.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] The implementations for these types of trie use vectorized CPU instructions to find the first set bit in a fixed-length key input (e.g.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] GCC's `__builtin_clz()` intrinsic function).
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Accordingly, the set bit is used to index the first item, or child node, in the 32- or 64-entry based bitwise tree.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Search then proceeds by testing each subsequent bit in the key.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] This procedure is also cache-local and highly parallelizable due to register independency, and thus performant on out-of-order execution CPUs.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Radix tree, also known as a **compressed trie**, is a space-optimized variant of a trie in which any node with only one child gets merged with its parent; elimination of branches of the nodes with a single child results in better metrics in both space and time.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] This works best when the trie remains static and set of keys stored are very sparse within their representation space.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] One more approach for static tries is to "pack" the trie by storing disjoint sets of children in the same memory location, interleaved.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Patricia trees are a particular implementation of the compressed binary trie that uses the binary encoding of the string keys in its representation.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Every node in a Patricia tree contains an index, known as a "skip number", that stores the node's branching index to avoid empty subtrees during traversal.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] A naive implementation of a trie consumes immense storage due to larger number of leaf-nodes caused by the sparse distribution of keys; Patricia trees can be efficient for such cases.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] A representation of a Patricia tree is shown to the right.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Each index value adjacent to the nodes represents the "skip number"—the index of the bit with which branching is to be decided.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] The skip number 1 at node 0 corresponds to the position 1 in the binary encoded ASCII where the leftmost bit differed in the key set X.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] The skip number is crucial for search, insertion, and deletion of nodes in the Patricia tree, and a bit masking operation is performed during every iteration.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Trie data structures are commonly used in predictive text or autocomplete dictionaries, and approximate matching algorithms.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Tries enable faster searches, occupy less space, especially when the set contains large number of short strings, thus used in spell checking, hyphenation applications and longest prefix match algorithms.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] However, if storing dictionary words is all that is required (i.e. there is no need to store metadata associated with each word), a minimal deterministic acyclic finite state automaton (DAFSA) or radix tree would use less storage space than a trie.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] This is because DAFSAs and radix trees can compress identical branches from the trie that correspond to the same suffixes (or parts) of different words being stored.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] String dictionaries are also utilized in natural language processing, such as finding lexicon of a text corpus.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Lexicographic sorting of a set of string keys can be implemented by building a trie for the given keys and traversing the tree in pre-order fashion; this is also a form of radix sort.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Tries are also fundamental data structures for burstsort, which is notable for being the fastest string sorting algorithm as of 2007, accomplished by its efficient use of CPU cache.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] A special kind of trie, called a suffix tree, can be used to index all suffixes in a text to carry out fast full-text searches.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] A specialized kind of trie called a compressed trie, is used in web search engines for storing the indexes - a collection of all searchable words.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Each terminal node is associated with a list of URLs—called occurrence list—to pages that match the keyword.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] The trie is stored in the main memory, whereas the occurrence is kept in an external storage, frequently in large clusters, or the in-memory index points to documents stored in an external location.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Tries are used in Bioinformatics, notably in sequence alignment software applications such as BLAST, which indexes all the different substrings of length *k* (called k-mers) of a text by storing the positions of their occurrences in a compressed trie sequence databases.
[src:aho-corasick-algorithm/trie] Compressed variants of tries, such as databases for managing Forwarding Information Base (FIB), are used in storing IP address prefixes within routers and bridges for prefix-based lookup to resolve mask-based operations in IP routing.
